<subSubSection id="84F6657DFFDDFFA1A6EA7FE2FEFCFB3F" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CC5336F6FFDDFFA1A6EA7FE2FEFCFB3F" blockId="4.[151,1437,908,1439]" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis id="FE98EAE4FFDDFFA1A6EA7FE2FE90FC5F" bold="true" box="[151,274,908,934]" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Medium to large size (
<quantity id="0B149B13FFDDFFA1A45F7FE2FD21FC5E" box="[546,675,908,935]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" unit="mm" value="27.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="15.0">15–40 mm</quantity>
). Head subcylindrical, long and narrow. Head slightly longer than pronotum. Antenniferous tubercles situated at or before middle of anteocular region. Genae tapering or rounded apically, not or only slightly surpassing apex of clypeus. First and third rostral segments much shorter than second. Third rostral segment shorter than first. Humeral angles rounded or angular but not spined. Scutellar process subcylindrical or subconical. Legs with all segments, except tarsi, uniformly dark. Fore femora usually long and slender; if relatively stout, at least 4.5 times as long as wide. Spongy fossula of males variable, from a small spongy fossula to absent in both fore and mid tibiae. Spongy fossula absent in females. Abdomen narrow to wide, with lateral portions of urotergites exposed or completely covered by hemelytra. Dorsal and ventral connexival segments normally developed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="84F6657DFFDDFFA1A6BA78BEFEBAFA66" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CC5336F6FFDDFFA1A6BA78BEFEBAFA66" blockId="4.[151,1437,908,1439]" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis id="FE98EAE4FFDDFFA1A6BA78BEFECDFB13" bold="true" box="[199,335,1232,1258]" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">Comments.</emphasis>
This group is diagnosed by a combination of characters of adult specimens. Nymphs might provide valuable taxonomical characters for generic classification (
<bibRefCitation id="A87D4B07FFDDFFA1A542789BFB01FAF6" author="Lent, H. &amp; Wygodzinsky, P." box="[831,1155,1268,1295]" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" pagination="123 - 520" refId="ref23125" refString="Lent, H. &amp; Wygodzinsky, P. (1979) Revision of the Triatominae (Hemiptera, Reduviidae) and their significance as vector of Chagas' disease. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 163, 123 - 520." type="journal article" year="1979">Lent &amp; Wygodzinsky, 1979</bibRefCitation>
), but still are underused in taxonomical practices. Some authors argued that species of the 
<taxonomicName id="0BEC4D75FFDDFFA1A5DF7977FBC0FACB" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[930,1090,1304,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Triatoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phyllosoma">
<emphasis id="FE98EAE4FFDDFFA1A5DF7977FBC0FACB" box="[930,1090,1304,1330]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">T. phyllosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex merit generic status (
<taxonomicName id="0BEC4D75FFDDFFA1A6DC7953FE45FAAE" authority="Carcavallo, 2000" authorityName="Carcavallo" authorityYear="2000" box="[161,455,1340,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Meccus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FE98EAE4FFDDFFA1A6DC7953FF75FAAF" box="[161,247,1341,1366]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">Meccus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="A87D4B07FFDDFFA1A77D7952FE45FAAE" author="Carcavallo, R. U. &amp; Jurberg, J. &amp; Lent, H. &amp; Noireau, F. &amp; Galvao, C." box="[256,455,1340,1367]" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" pagination="1 - 99" refId="ref20934" refString="Carcavallo, R. U., Jurberg, J., Lent, H., Noireau, F. &amp; Galvao, C. (2000) Phylogeny of the Triatominae (Hemiptera, Reduviidae). Proposals for taxonomic arrangements. Entomologia y Vectores, 7, 1 - 99." type="journal article" year="2000">Carcavallo, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
); however, the close phylogenetic relationship of 
<taxonomicName id="0BEC4D75FFDDFFA1A2757953FBDCFAAF" authorityName="Carcavallo" authorityYear="2000" box="[1032,1118,1341,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Meccus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FE98EAE4FFDDFFA1A2757953FBDCFAAF" box="[1032,1118,1341,1366]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">Meccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the remaining species groups supposes leaving 
<taxonomicName id="0BEC4D75FFDDFFA1A7C1790FFDA1FA83" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1832" box="[444,547,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Triatoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FE98EAE4FFDDFFA1A7C1790FFDA1FA83" box="[444,547,1377,1402]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">Triatoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
paraphyletic if the species assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="0BEC4D75FFDDFFA1A588790FFBC9FA83" authorityName="Carcavallo" authorityYear="2000" box="[1013,1099,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Meccus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FE98EAE4FFDDFFA1A588790FFBC9FA83" box="[1013,1099,1377,1402]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="339">Meccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were excluded (
<bibRefCitation id="A87D4B07FFDDFFA1A373790EFEAEFA66" author="Schofield, C. J. &amp; Galvao, C." pageId="4" pageNumber="339" pagination="88 - 100" refId="ref26242" refString="Schofield, C. J. &amp; Galvao, C. (2009) Classification, evolution, and species groups within the Triatominae. Acta Tropica, 110, 88 - 100. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. actatropica. 2009.01.010" type="journal article" year="2009">Schofield &amp; Galvão 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
